    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's more of a fierce, microscopic resource negotiation than a literal fight, though sometimes it feels like one! These microorganisms are constantly vying for the same sugars and starches in your flour. When the yeast (which loves simple sugars) and the lactic acid bacteria (which prefer to break down complex carbohydrates) are both present, they are in a dynamic balance.\n\nAt the microscopic level, the differences in their metabolic pathways are key. The yeast produces carbon dioxide gas, which causes the rise, and its activity is highly dependent on readily available sugars. The bacteria, on the other hand, produce lactic and acetic acids, which give your sourdough its tang. If one group suddenly multiplies faster than the other—perhaps due to a slight pH shift or a momentary spike in available food—their dominant metabolic output changes, leading to inconsistent rise and flavor.\n\nIt's a constant, microscopic tug-of-war over the available energy sources. Sometimes, the bacteria can temporarily dominate, producing more acid and slowing the yeast down, which is why you see inconsistent bubbling. It's a delicate, volatile balance, not a set schedule.\n\nTo bring it back to the practical, you can stabilize this by ensuring a consistent feeding ratio, which acts",
      "source": "target",
