      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To nudge the balance back towards the yeast, you need to give them a temporary advantage, which is usually achieved by adjusting the feeding strategy. If the bacteria are throwing the pH too low, you can try feeding it at a slightly higher ratio of flour to starter, effectively giving the yeast a bigger, fresher meal relative to the existing acidic mass.\n\nYou can also try using a slightly sweeter flour, if possible, as yeast generally prefers simpler, sweeter sugars to kickstart rapid activity. A very brief, slight increase in temperature (maybe just 1-2 degrees above your usual 75°F) can sometimes give the yeast a little metabolic boost to outpace the acid-loving bacteria for a short period.\n\nRemember, this is like trying to manage a very small, very volatile community; you don't want to overwhelm it, just gently guide the dominant species. If the starter is overly acidic, feeding it a bit more fresh, neutral flour can dilute the existing acids, giving the yeast a less hostile environment to thrive in.\n\nIt's a process of gentle coaxing, not forceful command. You are essentially managing the environment so that the yeast feels like it has the best spot on the crowded floor to start its feast",
